In deciding whether a company should pursue a certain project, there are two decision rules that they can use: the profitability index decision rule or the net present value (NPV) decision rule.

The **profitability index decision rule** is the ratio between the present value of future cash flows and the initial investment. A profit index value greater than $1$ indicates that the project is profitable.

In order to solve for the profitability index, we can simply use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Profitability index}&=\dfrac{\frac{\text{Future cash flow at Year 1}}{(1+\text{Required return})^1}+\frac{\text{Future cash flow at Year 2}}{(1+\text{Required return})^2}+\cdots+\frac{\text{Future cash flow at Year n}}{(1+\text{Required return})^n}}{\text{Initial investment}}
\end{aligned}$$

On the other hand, the **NPV decision rule** is basically taking the sum of all present value of future cash flows and subtracting the initial investment from them. A positive NPV means that the project is profitable while a negative NPV indicates a project that is at a loss. 

The formula for NPV is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=\left(\dfrac{\text{Future cash flow at Year 1}}{(1+\text{Required return})^1}+\dfrac{\text{Future cash flow at Year 2}}{(1+\text{Required return})^2}+\cdots+\dfrac{\text{Future cash flow at Year n}}{(1+\text{Required return})^n}\right)-\text{Initial investment}
\end{aligned}$$
